// Implement the circuit described by the Karnaugh map below.
// |       | a'b' | a'b  | ab  | ab' |
// |-------|------|------|-----|-----|
// | c'd'  | 0    | 1    | 0   | 1   |
// | c'd   | 1    | 0    | 1   | 0   |
// | cd    | 0    | 1    | 0   | 1   |
// | cd'   | 1    | 0    | 1   | 0   |

// Try to simplify the k-map before coding it. Try both product-of-sums and sum-of-products forms. We can't check whether you have the optimal simplification of the k-map. But we can check if your reduction is equivalent, and we can check whether you can translate a k-map into a circuit.


module top_module(
    input a,
    input b,
    input c,
    input d,
    output out  ); 

    assign out = (~a & b & c & d) | (~a & b & ~c & ~d) | (a & ~b & c & d) | (a & ~b & ~c & d) | (a & b & ~c & ~d) | (a & b & c & ~d);

endmodule

// |-------|------|------|-----|-----|

// Try to simplify the k-map before coding it. Try both product-of-sums and sum-of-products forms. We can't check whether you have the optimal simplification of the k-map. But we can check if your reduction is equivalent, and we can check whether you can translate a k-map into a circuit.


module top_module(
    input a,
    input b,
    input c,
    input d,
    output out  ); 

    assign out = (~a & b & c & d) | (~a & b & ~c & ~d) | (a & ~b & c & d) | (a & ~b & ~c & d) | (a & b & ~c & ~d) | (a & b & c & ~d);

original text:  // Implement the circuit described by the Karnaugh map below.
// |       | a'b' | a'b  | ab  | ab' |
// |-------|------|------|-----|-----|
// | c'd'  | 0    | 1    | 0   | 1   |
// | c'd   | 1    | 0    | 1   | 0   |
// | cd    | 0    | 1    | 0   | 1   |
// | cd'   | 1    | 0    | 1   | 0   |

// Try to simplify the k-map before coding it. Try both product-of-sums and sum-of-products forms. We can't check whether you have the optimal simplification of the k-map. But we can check if your reduction is equivalent, and we can check whether you can translate a k-map into a circuit.


module top_module(
    input a,
    input b,
    input c,
    input d,
    output out  ); 

    assign out = a | b | c | d;
    
    // This is ok too: assign out = a & b & c & d;
    
    // This is not ok: the output is X if any of the input is X.
    // The truth table shows that "out = a & b & c & d;" is ok.
    // It is the reduction that is not ok.
    
    // The reduction can be fixed by adding a "0" input to the k-map.
    // The truth table shows that "out = a & b & c & d & 0;" is ok.
    // The k-map is now:

original text:  // Implement the circuit described by the Karnaugh map below.
// |       | a'b' | a'b  | ab  | ab' |
// |-------|------|------|-----|-----|
// | c'd'  | 0    | 1    | 0   | 1   |
// | c'd   | 1    | 0    | 1   | 0   |
// | cd    | 0    | 1    | 0   | 1   |
// | cd'   | 1    | 0    | 1   | 0   |

// Try to simplify the k-map before coding it. Try both product-of-sums and sum-of-products forms. We can't check whether you have the optimal simplification of the k-map. But we can check if your reduction is equivalent, and we can check whether you can translate a k-map into a circuit.

original text:  // Implement the circuit described by the Karnaugh map below.
// |       | a'b' | a'b  | ab  | ab' |
// |-------|------|------|-----|-----|
// | c'd'  | 0    | 1    | 0   | 1   |
// | c'd   | 1    | 0    | 1   | 0   |
// | cd    | 0    | 1    | 0   | 1   |
// | cd'   | 1    | 0    | 1   | 0   |

// Try to simplify the k-map before coding it. Try both product-of-sums and sum-of-products forms. We can't check whether you have the optimal simplification of the k-map. But we can check if your reduction is equivalent, and we can check whether you can translate a k-map into a circuit.


module top_module(
    input a,
    input b,
    input c,
    input d,
    output out  ); 
    assign out = (~a & ~b & ~c & d) | (~a & b & ~c & ~d) | (a & ~b & c & d) | (a & b & ~c & d);

endmodule

original text:  // Implement the circuit described by the Karnaugh map below.
// |       | a'b' | a'b  | ab  | ab' |
// |-------|------|------|-----|-----|
// | c'd'  | 0    | 1    | 0   | 1   |
// | c'd   | 1    | 0    | 1   | 0   |
// | cd    | 0    | 1    | 0   | 1   |
// | cd'   | 1    | 0    | 1   | 0   |

// Try to simplify the k-map before coding it. Try both product-of-sums and sum-of-products forms. We can't check whether you have the optimal simplification of the k-map. But we can check if your reduction is equivalent, and we can check whether you can translate a k-map into a circuit.


module top_module(
    input a,
    input b,
    input c,
    input d,
    output out  ); 

    assign out = (~a & b & c) | (~a & b & ~c & d) | (a & ~b & c) | (a & ~b & ~c & d);

original text:  // Implement the circuit described by the Karnaugh map below.
// |       | a'b' | a'b  | ab  | ab' |
// |-------|------|------|-----|-----|
// | c'd'  | 0    | 1    | 0   | 1   |
// | c'd   | 1    | 0    | 1   | 0   |
// | cd    | 0    | 1    | 0   | 1   |
// | cd'   | 1    | 0    | 1   | 0   |

// Try to simplify the k-map before coding it. Try both product-of-sums and sum-of-products forms. We can't check whether you have the optimal simplification of the k-map. But we can check if your reduction is equivalent, and we can check whether you can translate a k-map into a circuit.


module top_module(
    input a,
    input b,
    input c,
    input d,
    output out  ); 
    assign out = (~a & ~b & ~c & d) | (~a & b & ~c & ~d) | (a & ~b & c & d) | (a & b & ~c & d) | (a & b & c & ~d);

original text:  // Implement the circuit described by the Karnaugh map below.
// |       | a'b' | a'b  | ab  | ab' |
// |-------|------|------|-----|-----|
// | c'd'  | 0    | 1    | 0   | 1   |
// | c'd   | 1    | 0    | 1   | 0   |
// | cd    | 0    | 1    | 0   | 1   |
// | cd'   | 1    | 0    | 1   | 0   |

// Try to simplify the k-map before coding it. Try both product-of-sums and sum-of-products forms. We can't check whether you have the optimal simplification of the k-map. But we can check if your reduction is equivalent, and we can check whether you can translate a k-map into a circuit.


module top_module(
    input a,
    input b,
    input c,
    input d,
    output out  ); 
    assign out = (~a & b & c & d) | (~a & ~b & ~c & d) | (a & ~b & ~c & d) | (a & b & ~c & d);

endmodule

// Implement the circuit described by the Karnaugh map below.
// |       | a'b' | a'b  | ab  | ab' |
// |-------|------|------|-----|-----|
// | c'd'  | 0    | 1    | 0   | 1   |
// | c'd   | 1    | 0    | 1   | 0   |
// | cd    | 0    | 1    | 0   | 1   |
// | cd'   | 1    | 0    | 1   | 0   |

// Try to simplify the k-map before coding it. Try both product-of-sums and sum-of-products forms. We can't check whether you have the optimal simplification of the k-map. But we can check if your reduction is equivalent, and we can check whether you can translate a k-map into a circuit.


module top_module(
    input a,
    input b,
    input c,
    input d,
    output out  ); 
    assign out = (~a & ~b & ~c & d) | (~a & b & ~c & ~d) | (a & ~b & c & d) | (a & b & ~c & d) | (a & b & c & ~d);

endmodule

// |       | a'b' | a'b  | ab  | ab' |
// |-------|------|------|-----|-----|
// | c'd'  | 0    | 1    | 0   | 1   |

// | cd'   | 1    | 0    | 1   | 0   |

// | c'd   | 1    | 0    | 1   | 0   |
// | cd    | 0    | 1    | 0   | 1   |
// | cd'   | 1    | 0    | 1   | 0   |

// Try to simplify the k-map before coding it. Try both product-of-sums and sum-of-products forms. We can't check whether you have the optimal simplification of the k-map. But we can check if your reduction is equivalent, and we can check whether you can translate a k-map into a circuit.


module top_module(
    input a,
    input b,

// Try to simplify the k-map before coding it. Try both product-of-sums and sum-of-products forms. We can't check whether you have the optimal simplification of the k-map. But we can check if your reduction is equivalent, and we can check whether you can translate a k-map into a circuit.


module top_module(
    input a,
    input b,
    input c,
    input d,
    output out  ); 

    assign out = (a&b) | (c&d);

    /*
    assign out = (a&b) + (c&d);
    assign out = (a|b) & (c|d);
    assign out = (a|b) ^ (c|d);

// |       | a'b' | a'b  | ab  | ab' |
// |-------|------|------|-----|-----|

// | c'd   | 1    | 0    | 1   | 0   |

// | cd'   | 1    | 0    | 1   | 0   |

// Try to simplify the k-map before coding it. Try both product-of-sums and sum-of-products forms. We can't check whether you have the optimal simplification of the k-map. But we can check if your reduction is equivalent, and we can check whether you can translate a k-map into a circuit.


module top_module(
    input a,
    input b,
    input c,
    input d,
    output out  );

    /*
    assign out = (a&b) + (c&d);

original text:  // Implement the circuit described by the Karnaugh map below.
// |       | a'b' | a'b  | ab  | ab' |
// |-------|------|------|-----|-----|
// | c'd'  | 0    | 1    | 0   | 1   |
// | c'd   | 1    | 0    | 1   | 0   |
// | cd    | 0    | 1    | 0   | 1   |
// | cd'   | 1    | 0    | 1   | 0   |

// Try to simplify the k-map before coding it. Try both product-of-sums and sum-of-products forms. We can't check whether you have the optimal simplification of the k-map. But we can check if your reduction is equivalent, and we can check whether you can translate a k-map into a circuit.


module top_module(
    input a,
    input b,
    input c,
    input d,
    output out  ); 
    assign out = (~a & ~b & ~c & d) | (~a & b & ~c & ~d) | (a & ~b & c & d) | (a & b & ~c & d);

endmodule

original text:  // Implement the circuit described by the Karnaugh map below.
// |       | a'b' | a'b  | ab  | ab' |
// |-------|------|------|-----|-----|
// | c'd'  | 0    | 1    | 0   | 1   |
// | c'd   | 1    | 0    | 1   | 0   |
// | cd    | 0    | 1    | 0   | 1   |
// | cd'   | 1    | 0    | 1   | 0   |

// Try to simplify the k-map before coding it. Try both product-of-sums and sum-of-products forms. We can't check whether you have the optimal simplification of the k-map. But we can check if your reduction is equivalent, and we can check whether you can translate a k-map into a circuit.


module top_module(
    input a,
    input b,
    input c,
    input d,
    output out  ); 

    assign out = (~a & ~b & ~c & d) | (~a & b & ~c & ~d) | (a & ~b & c & d) | (a & b & ~c & d);

endmodule

// Implement the circuit described by the Karnaugh map below.
// |       | a'b' | a'b  | ab  | ab' |
// |-------|------|------|-----|-----|
// | c'd'  | 0    | 1    | 0   | 1   |
// | c'd   | 1    | 0    | 1   | 0   |
// | cd    | 0    | 1    | 0   | 1   |
// | cd'   | 1    | 0    | 1   | 0   |

// Try to simplify the k-map before coding it. Try both product-of-sums and sum-of-products forms. We can't check whether you have the optimal simplification of the k-map. But we can check if your reduction is equivalent, and we can check whether you can translate a k-map into a circuit.


module top_module(
    input a,
    input b,
    input c,
    input d,
    output out  ); 
    assign out = (~a & ~b & ~c & d) | (~a & b & ~c & ~d) | (a & ~b & c & d) | (a & b & ~c & d) | (a & b & c & ~d);

endmodule

// |-------|------|------|-----|-----|
// | c'd'  | 0    | 1    | 0   | 1   |

// | cd    | 0    | 1    | 0   | 1   |
// | cd'   | 1    | 0    | 1   | 0   |

// Try to simplify the k-map before coding it. Try both product-of-sums and sum-of-products forms. We can't check whether you have the optimal simplification of the k-map. But we can check if your reduction is equivalent, and we can check whether you can translate a k-map into a circuit.


module top_module(
    input a,
    input b,
    input c,
    input d,
    output out  );

original text:  // Implement the circuit described by the Karnaugh map below.
// |       | a'b' | a'b  | ab  | ab' |
// |-------|------|------|-----|-----|
// | c'd'  | 0    | 1    | 0   | 1   |
// | c'd   | 1    | 0    | 1   | 0   |
// | cd    | 0    | 1    | 0   | 1   |
// | cd'   | 1    | 0    | 1   | 0   |

// Try to simplify the k-map before coding it. Try both product-of-sums and sum-of-products forms. We can't check whether you have the optimal simplification of the k-map. But we can check if your reduction is equivalent, and we can check whether you can translate a k-map into a circuit.


module top_module(
    input a,
    input b,
    input c,
    input d,
    output out  ); 

    assign out = (a&b) | (a&c) | (a&d) | (b&c) | (b&d) | (c&d);

endmodule
